 </div>
 <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
 <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
 <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">Freight &amp; Packaging Cost Reduction</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">40-50% smaller volume vs silicon at the same wattage reduces per-unit packaging dimensions and container density. For a 5,000-unit OEM order, GaN saves <strong>$0.50-2.00/unit in freight</strong> and allows ~30% more units per pallet — a direct margin gain before retail pricing.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
 <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">Field Return Rate Impact</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">WOWOHCOOL GaN V chargers have a measured field return rate of <strong>below 0.3%</strong> across 2M+ units shipped, compared to ~3.2% for equivalent silicon chargers. Lower operating temperatures (GaN: 52°C vs Silicon: 77°C at 65W full load) reduce thermal stress on electrolytic capacitors — the #1 failure component in chargers.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
 <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">Multi-Port Architecture Without Compromise</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">GaN's higher switching frequency (5 MHz+ for GaN V) enables 2C1A and 3C1A multi-port designs that silicon cannot support without excessive heat. A single GaN charger can replace 2-3 separate chargers with dynamic power allocation — the key selling point for premium retail ($35+ price point) where multi-port is now baseline expectation.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200 shadow-sm">
 <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">Regulatory Tailwind: EU USB-C Mandate</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">The EU Common Charger Directive (2022/2380) mandates USB-C for all laptops sold in the EU from <strong>April 28, 2026</strong>. Since GaN is the only practical technology for compact 65W+ USB-C laptop chargers, this regulation creates a non-optional replacement cycle across Europe's laptop charger market — estimated at <strong>40-50 million units annually</strong>. OEM brands without GaN products above 65W are locked out of this segment.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-brandBlue/10 border-l-4 border-brandBlue p-6 mt-8 rounded-r-xl">
  <h4 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">Important: GaN ≠ PD (Power Delivery)</h4>
  <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">GaN is a <strong>semiconductor material</strong> (hardware), while PD (Power Delivery) is a <strong>charging protocol</strong> (software standard). They complement each other — a GaN charger uses gallium nitride transistors for efficiency and compactness, while PD defines how power is negotiated between charger and device. The industry baseline in 2026 is <strong>GaN + PD 3.1 + PPS</strong> — all three working together.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 </section>
 <blockquote class="bg-slate-50 border-l-4 border-brandBlue p-6 rounded-r-xl mb-12 not-italic">
 <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-3">"GaN is not just a material upgrade — it's a fundamental shift in power electronics architecture. The wide bandgap properties enable switching frequencies that were physically impossible with silicon, unlocking form factors that redefine what a charger can be."</p>
 <cite class="text-sm text-slate-500 not-italic">— Dr. Alex Lidow, CEO of Efficient Power Conversion (EPC), <em>IEEE Power Electronics Magazine</em>, 2025</cite>
 </blockquote>
